Officially down 8 pounds since November 1st! I made these tiny and sustainable adjustments to my daily routine:
1.  I stopped buying cheese.  If it’s in the house, I’ll eat it.
2.  I started walking on the treadmill as soon as the alarm goes off.  Only for 5 minutes, and just a slow walk.
3.  I added Apple Cider Vinegar, lemon and a dash of cinnamon and cayenne pepper to the 16 Oz of water I was already drinking upon waking up. 

Share your personal slim-down tips with everyone below!

-Aerosmith

This song “Pink” always brings back a beautiful childhood memory…
My school dance team made it to the ADA national dance competition one year.  There was a girl from a different team, who competed in the solo division to this song. 
I’d never seen someone dance with so much love. 
I remember watching her and thinking, “I wanna dance like that!” She just looked so happy, and you could tell she really loved what she was doing. 
She inspired me and from that point on, I always tried to pour that kind of love into whatever I was doing. 💕

Here’s to strong women everywhere, on this International Women’s Day! 
When was the last time you felt fearless? Untouchable? Beautiful?  Think about it today and write it down.  Post it.  Take pride in it. 
For years, a man told me: “You’re not an athlete.  Running isn’t a sport.  Running is exercise.  Congrats on your participation medal.” 
Never let anyone minimize you!
I used those words as fuel last Saturday. 
It pushed me to a personal record in the half marathon, and I found great strength in that accomplishment.
So on this day of female celebration, know that whatever YOUR finish line is, you can either get there on your own, or one day someone who appreciates your strength will be waiting for you. 💕

Boston, I love you! 💙💛💙💛
You awaken my wild soul.  You give me strength and confidence.  You celebrate me, but you humble me.
Our relationship may be volatile at times, but we are connected and I will always come back for more. 
On Monday, April 17th, I completed my 3rd Boston Marathon and 20th full marathon. 
It was such a fun but treacherous day… 
yet looking back, I wouldn’t have changed a thing. 
I went into this race with achilles tendonitis and lost 6 weeks of full training. 
I knew I’d be racing on muscle memory alone, so I really didn’t know what to expect. I told myself I would walk if anything hurt and kept in mind that I still want to be running at age 100, so nothing is worth an even bigger injury. 
@emaywarren and I ran together for  17 miles, and it was so fun to watch her enjoy her first Boston. 
Shortly after mile 17, I started feeling pain crawl up my hamstring, then into the opposite quad and knee.  Everything was shutting down.  The KT Tape took the pain off my lower legs, but the new pain was a product of compensation.  I experienced two firsts this race… #1 walking made it worse, but I did have to walk for a bit. 
#2… I had to stop at the Med tent.
The medics were so wonderful and sprayed my legs with what I can only imagine was liquid crack. 
Between the walking and the tent, I lost around 15 minutes on the clock. 
My legs turned into concrete the last 4 miles, so I can’t believe I finished at all, let alone in 3:49.  I was very lucky nothing tore.  Next order of business is getting healthy and getting back on the race course. 
Until next time Boston! Can’t wait to chase the unicorn again! 🦄

So honored to serve as emcee for another @gotr_greaterhouston 5k at @riceuniversity this morning! 
I hold these girls so close to my heart.  Every race is truly unique and special, but today stood out. 
After my emcee duties, I always run the race with the girls. 
During today’s the race, a little girl grabbed my arm and asked me to run with her and take care of her.  I was giving her pointers and cheering her on.  When I told her to kick at the end, she took off like a rocket.  I’ve never seen a kick like that before!  Her name is Avery and she’s only 10 years old.  After the race, she crossed the finish line, got a little sick, then looked at me, asked if she won and said, “that was awesome!” 😂  Lol that’s what it’s all about.  Blood, sweat, tears and a lil 🤮! 
Avery, I don’t know who your parents are, but they raised one tough chick and I was so delighted to run with you today.  Truly made my weekend! 
Here’s to another epic race with the best organization in town! 🏃🏻‍♀️🥇🏁

Another experience with @beastpacing!  Today I paced the 2:10 group in the Hometown Half Marathon in Sugar Land.  Of all the races I’ve paced so far, today was by far the most rewarding.  The first photo is with a runner named Amil.  Today was his first-ever half marathon, and boy what a difficult one to choose for a first!  It was extremely hot and humid, with barely any shade.  One of the water stops ran out of water.  Amil caught up with me and my pace partner Tuy and he was struggling, but I knew he had some push left.  Since we’re allowed a bit of a buffer on the front end of our assigned pace times, I pulled away with Amil and despite his hip pain, he had an incredible kick at the end. ☀️Down 5 lbs. & feeling better☀️

If you’re interested in slimming down by making small changes, here’s what I did these past couple months:

1. As soon as I wake up, I upped my water intake to 32 oz. over 16 oz. (64-80 per day)

2. Black coffee only! Never sugar or cream

3. Reduced my weekly running mileage to 15 miles or less and started lifting heavy weights (no race until November)

4. Bagged candy started giving me migraines, so I’m forever done 

5. I drink sparkling water to curb any sweet cravings during the week 

6.  Swapped crunches for full sit-ups 

7.  M-F… I immediately jump on the treadmill and walk 15 min on M & F, then 10 min T, W, Th.  That way, if I miss a workout or eat something bad, I’ve built-in an additional hour of doing something active that week

Pool time was definitely more fun today and my lower back is also feeling better from doing more squats. 

Please drop any helpful tips you have/do for others in the caption. ❤️

Leg day is done! 
Had a rough morning at the Cypress Half Marathon, but I pushed through it.  When you go into a race injured, you have a 3 choices:  walk it, jog it and forget about your time or see how hard you can push and adjust accordingly. 
I probably should’ve jogged, but I went out hard and crossed my fingers knowing I’d eventually have to slow down.  7:11/7:13/7:15/7:14 for the first 4 miles, then my knee and quad started screaming.  I raced smart, listened to my body and pulled back in 30 second increments. 
Time to get healthy, so the next race is solid!

I recently asked my 7-year-old son Dash to make up a story about anything he wanted. I only planned to record it and save it for myself, but when I played it back, I realized it was a metaphor for the year.  I had to navigate through some difficulties, but I handled it all and moved on. 
This year was a total win! 
Maybe Dash made up that story from scratch, or maybe he understands more than I realize.  Whatever the reason, he chose me as his main character without even thinking.  And in life, he is MY main character. 
I am so lucky to have that beautiful child, in addition to all the wonderful memories with family and friends.  What a way to end 2023!

Here’s your feel good story of the day, and one that’s close to my heart! Thousands of athletes will be running in the @chevronhoustonmarathon this weekend, and some of those runners participating are blind.  As some of you know, I’ve been volunteering with Team Catapult, which is an organization that helps athletes with disabilities achieve their goals in endurance sports, like marathons. 
I’m proud to introduce you to this team, and show you how they’ve been preparing for this weekend! 

If you’d like to get involved, check out their website: 
Teamcatapult.org, where you can find information on guide training, weekly workouts and how to make donations.

So much to say about this special day!  It was my first time guiding a visually-impaired athlete in a full marathon, and being paired with @noe_rivas_vicentino and guiding with @c_charlie7451 made it even more memorable. Noe shaved 3 minutes off his best time for a new PR!  I also want to thank Sara for snapping those unexpected pics at the finish line.  Raw emotion lives in the moments, when we don’t know people are watching.  Me looking at my watch, realizing he got a PR, then Noe hugging me and saying, “Te amo Stephanie. Gracias.” 🥹 A huge thank you to Carlos as well, for being the best yin and yang guide duo!
